{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b79e861d-b4dc-4c21-a2df-ed35aeb6f378","content":"No repo files here — this is a general guidance question. Here's how to migrate:\n\n## Key Changes\n\n**1. Replace `VSTest@3` with `DotNetCoreCLI@2` (or a plain `dotnet test` script)**\n\nMicrosoft.Testing.Platform runs via `dotnet test` — it doesn't use `vstest.console.exe`, so `VSTest@3` won't work.\n\n**2. Enable TRX reports** by passing the TRX logger:\n\n```yaml\n- task: DotNetCoreCLI@2\n  displayName: 'Run Tests'\n  inputs:\n    command: test\n    projects: '**/*.Tests.csproj'\n    arguments: >-\n      --configuration Release\n      --logger \"trx;LogFilePrefix=TestResults\"\n      --results-directory $(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults\n```\n\nOr equivalently as a script step:\n\n```yaml\n- script: >-\n    dotnet test\n    --configuration Release\n    --logger \"trx;LogFilePrefix=TestResults\"\n    --results-directory $(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults\n  displayName: 'Run Tests'\n```\n\n**3. Publish test results** (since `DotNetCoreCLI@2` doesn't auto-publish like `VSTest@3`):\n\n```yaml\n- task: PublishTestResults@2\n  displayName: 'Publish Test Results'\n  inputs:\n    testResultsFormat: VSTest\n    testResultsFiles: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/*.trx'\n  condition: always()\n```\n\n**4. Collect code coverage** — add a coverage collector:\n\n```yaml\n# In your test arguments, add:\narguments: >-\n  --configuration Release\n  --logger \"trx;LogFilePrefix=TestResults\"\n  --results-directory $(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults\n  --collect \"Code Coverage\"\n```\n\nThen publish it:\n\n```yaml\n- task: PublishCodeCoverageResults@2\n  displayName: 'Publish Code Coverage'\n  inputs:\n    summaryFileLocation: '$(Agent.TempDirectory)/TestResults/**/*.cobertura.xml'\n  condition: always()\n```\n\n> If using Coverlet instead of the built-in collector, replace `--collect \"Code Coverage\"` with `--collect:\"XPlat Code Coverage\"` and ensure the `coverlet.collector` NuGet package is referenced in your test projects.\n\n## Summary of what's replaced\n\n| Before (VSTest@3) | After (Microsoft.Testing.Platform) |\n|---|---|\n| `VSTest@3` task | `DotNetCoreCLI@2` or `script: dotnet test` |\n| Auto-published TRX | `PublishTestResults@2` (manual) |\n| Built-in coverage | `--collect` flag + `PublishCodeCoverageResults@2` |\n\nMake sure your test projects reference `Microsoft.Testing.Platform` (and `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` if needed) via NuGet.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"afd3b26a-65b0-4198-927d-db2d0d8ff6c3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty, so this is a general question rather than a codebase-specific task. Let me provide guidance on migrating from VSTest@3 to Microsoft.Testing.Platform in Azure DevOps CI pipelines.","outputTokens":787,"requestId":"3430:2ADC27:74A8E20:80FB5AB:69F3FAD6"},"id":"24237b03-77de-47e7-a816-457c6b2b0e63","timestamp":"2026-05-01T00:59:20.144Z","parentId":"69d3b408-a4e1-42b8-894e-af86cbed6b45"}
